Roger Brown's College Notebook: Pinkerton product Polichetti settling into college baseball

By ROGER BROWN
March 19. 2017 1:11AM




Pinkerton grad John Polichetti is adjusting to college-level pitching in his first season at UMass Lowell. (Photo Courtesy of UMass Lowell)
UMASS-LOWELL freshman John Polichetti may have turned a corner in his collegiate baseball career last week when he collected five hits in three games (.455) and was named the America East Rookie of the Week.Polichetti had five hits in 11 at-bats, scored a run and drove in a run in Lowell's three victories: a doubleheader sweep of Manhattan and a 6-5 triumph over Delaware. He reached base in six of his 12 at-bats.Polichetti, an Atkinson resident who played high school baseball at Pinkerton Academy in Derry, said adjusting to college pitching has been difficult, but that his success last week helped his confidence at the plate. "The biggest difference for me is in high school you'd see one really good pitcher every few weeks, and in college you're facing a really good pitcher every day," Polichetti explained. "Across the board a (college) pitcher's ability to locate all three of his pitches is the biggest difference."My (offensive) numbers are low right now (he was batting .222 through 14 games) and I'm striking out more than I'm used to, but last week was really the first week where I was getting multiple hits per game and feeling good at the plate. It definitely was a breakout week for me."Polichetti had two hits, drove in three runs and walked once in Thursday's 13-6 victory over William & Mary. Although he played multiple positions in high school, Polichetti may have been known best as a pitcher during his days at Pinkerton. He's Lowell's starting third baseman and has been hitting sixth in the batting order. He said he may pitch in some midweek games for Lowell, but is concentrating on his offense and playing third."My mentality hasn't changed," he said. "Whatever the coach needs from me. I just wanted to find a way on the field and get to play every day. I'm grateful for the opportunity I have, but I don't want to get too comfortable because that's when things can get taken away from you."BaseballBrentwood's Jared Brescia, a freshman second baseman at Assumption, was named the Northeast-10 Rookie of the Week on Monday. Brescia hit .500 with a .636 on-base percentage to help Assumption post a 3-2 record in five games played in Florida. He had multiple hits in four of the five games, drew four walks, scored twice, stole two bases and had two RBIs.Brescia entered Saturday's doubleheader against New Haven batting .400 (16 for 40) and had collected at least one hit in 11 of Assumption's 13 games.Deerfield's Josh Partridge, a relief pitcher on the St. Joseph's College baseball team, was selected as the Great Northeast Athletic Conference Pitcher of the Week and was named to the D3Baseball.com Team of the Week on Monday. Partridge, who played at Concord High School, posted a 0.00 ERA in three relief appearances during the week. He recorded nine strikeouts, allowed three hits and didn't walk a batter in 8 2/3 innings. SoftballRochester's Shannon Colson, an outfielder on the St. Anselm College softball team, was named the Northeast-10 Conference's Rookie of the Week on Monday after she hit .391 (9 for 23) with a .462 on-base percentage during the first eight games of her college career.Men's basketballPlymouth State senior Jack Preston (Nashua) and freshman Jaylen Leroy (Manchester) were recently recognized by the the Little East Conference. Preston, a 6-foot-6 forward, was an LEC First-Team selection, and Leroy, a 6-foot-2 guard, was named to the LEC All-Rookie Team.Preston averaged 18.1 points and 8.1 rebounds per game last season. Leroy averaged 11.0 points per game and made 47 3-pointers, the most among freshmen in the league.Dartmouth sophomore Evan Boudreaux was named to the All-Ivy League Second Team last week. Boudreaux, a 6-foot-8 forward, finished the season as the Ivy League's leader in rebounding (9.5 per game) and ranked second in scoring (17.5 ppg). He was Dartmouth's leading rebounder in 25 of its 27 games and was the team's leading scorer in 21 contests.Colby-Sawyer sophomore Jourdain Bell was named to the Eastern College Athletic Conference Division III New England Men's Basketball First Team.Bell, a Manchester resident, averaged a team-high 20.1 points per game. He also led the Chargers in steals (54) and was second in assists (97). He ranked 18th nationally among Division III players in minutes players and was 40th in points scored.Londonderry's Marc Corey, a sophomore forward at St. Joseph's College, was named to the Great Northeast Athletic Conference Second Team. Corey averaged 10.8 points. 5.4 rebounds and 3.1 assists per game last season. He led the team in made 3-point shots with 39.Portsmouth's Harry Rafferty, a senior at Wesleyan, was named to the NESCAC Second Team after he averaged 13 points per game in 26 contests last season.Women's basketballRochester's Emily Benway, a sophomore forward at St. Joseph's College, was selected to the Maine Women's Basketball Coaches' Association All-State Second Team. Benway averaged 13.5 points and a team-high 8.7 rebounds per game during the 2016-17 season.Women's hockeySt. Anselm College coach Kerstin Matthews has been named one of eight finalists for the CCM American Hockey Coaches' Association Women's College Division Coach of the Year on Tuesday.Matthews, who was named the New England Hockey Conference Coach of the Year last month, led St. Anselm to NEHC regular-season and NEHC Open championships last season, when the Hawks posted a 22-2-3 record. The regular-season title was St. Anselm's first since 2007-08. It was the third time in the last four years the Hawks have won at least 20 games.Track and fieldKeene State senior Katelyn Terry was named the Little East Conference Women's Indoor Track Athlete of the Year. Terry, a Strafford resident, turned in a strong performance at the LEC/New England Alliance Championships, where she placed first in the 400-meter dash with a season-best time of 58.46. She also finished second in the 800 (2:21.91) and was fifth in the triple jump (10.56). Terry was also a part of the 4x400 relay that finished first (4:08.41).Plymouth State University sophomore Sam Brunnette was named the Little East Conference Men's Indoor Track Athlete of the Year, and freshman Derek Davies (Londonderry) was selected as the LEC Men's Indoor Field Athlete of the Year.Brunnette finished fifth in the mile at the New England Division III Championships in 4:17.84. He currently has the ninth fastest time in New England in both the mile and the 3,000 meters, and ranks 33rd nationally in the 3,000 and 49th in the mile.A freshman pole vaulter, Davies placed third in the New England Alliance and second among LEC vaulters at the LEC Championships. His mark of 4.10 meters (13-5.25) matched his season-high and was ranked 17th in New England at that time. He placed 14th at the New England Division III Championships with a mark of 3.95 meters. His personal best of 4.10 meters ranks 19th in New England.Moravian College senior Meg Brockett competed at the NCAA Division III Indoor Track & Field national championships earlier this month at North Central (Ill.) College. Brockett, a Hampton resident who attended Manchester Central, battled through an injury to finish 17th in the 5,000-meter run (19:26.56).Strafford's Jeremy Brassard won the first national championship of his college career by winning the 1,000 meters at the NAIA Indoor National Championships on March 4. Brassard, who attended Coe-Brown in Northwood, completed the event in 2:16.18, which broke the school record set in 2015.Swimming and divingSimmons College coach Mindy Williams, a Hampstead resident, was named the New England Intercollegiate Swimming and Diving Association Coach of the Year.Williams guided Simmons to the program's highest finish in school history, a second-place finish among 21 teams at the NEISDA Championship. The Sharks won their 13th straight Great Northeast Athletic Conference Championship and posted a 12-0 record in dual meets.Women's lacrosseTwo Keene State players were honored by the Little East Conference on Monday.Senior Alison Argiro was named the LEC Goalkeeper of the Week after she made six saves in a 16-3 loss to eighth-ranked Amherst. She ranks third among LEC goalkeepers in saves with 26. Freshman attack Gabby Smith, a Laconia resident, was selected as the LEC Rookie of the Week after she scored twice against Amherst. Men's lacrosseKeene State junior Mathew Howe was selected as the Little East Conference Goalkeeper of the Week following a 14-save performance in a 24-16 loss to third-ranked Tufts. Howe, a Bedford native, entered the week third in the league with 42 saves.Field hockeyFive members of the University of New Hampshire field hockey team were named to the 2016 ZAG Field Hockey/National Field Hockey Coaches' Association Division I National Academic Squad: freshman Kayla Sliz, senior Lindsey Nerbonne (Bow), junior Brittany Marshall (Hopkinton), junior Kallie Gray and junior Madelyn McAteer.UNH also received a ZAG Field Hockey/NFHCA Division I National Academic Team Award for achieving a minimum team grade-point average of 3.0 for the first semester of the 2016-17 academic year.Roger Brown compiles the college notebook for the New Hampshire Sunday News. He can be reached at rbrown@unionleader.com.
